**First clone of this repo?** Hook + MCP wiring lives in
`.claude/settings.local.json` and `.mcp.json` (both gitignored - they bake
absolute, per-machine paths). The graph file travels with the repo, the
plumbing does not. Run `weave init` once after cloning and restart this
session to pick up the MCP server and hooks.

**Native tools:** if the weave MCP server is connected you have tools
`weave_status`, `weave_inbox`, `weave_add`, `weave_set`, `weave_link`,
`weave_focus`, `weave_ls`, `weave_show`, `weave_ask` - prefer them.
Otherwise use the CLI:  `WEAVE`  (identical operations).

**At session start** the weave hook prints current state. Also run
`weave inbox` if it reports unread items - those are messages from the human.

**Workflow:**
- Before non-trivial work, run `weave status` to see focus, tasks, questions.
- When you form a plan: `weave add plan "<title>" --body "<summary>"`, then add
  a `task` node per step (`weave add task "<step>" --parent <planId>`), then
  `weave focus <planId>`.
- As work progresses: `weave set <taskId> --status doing|done|blocked`.
- Record meaningful choices: `weave add decision "<choice>" --body "<why>"
  --parent <planId>`.
- Files you edit are auto-tracked into the graph by a hook - no action needed.
- When you need a human decision, DO NOT just ask in chat - also create it so
  it shows in their workspace:
  `weave add question "<question>" --author claude --parent <planId>`.
- Resolve it later with `weave set <questionId> --status resolved`.
- Link related nodes: `weave link <from> <to> <rel>`
  (rels: implements, depends_on, blocks, relates_to, supersedes, produces).
- **Context routing:** attach the files a task needs with
  `weave attach <taskId> <path>...` (paths or folder nodes). Before starting a
  task run `weave context <taskId>` (or the `weave_context` tool) - it gives
  you the exact reading list, inherited from parent plans plus the task's own.
  The session hook prints reading lists for the focus plan and active tasks
  automatically, so keep them attached and you always know what to load.

**More commands worth knowing:**
- `weave search "<text>"` - free-text across titles, bodies, tags.
- `weave history` / `weave undo [--to <rev>]` - rolling snapshots; safe to
  revert an accidental edit, then `undo --to <higher rev>` redoes it.
- `weave pin <node>` / `weave archive <node>` - memory tiers. Archived
  nodes are excluded from this hook and from `weave status`; pinned ones
  are surfaced at the top.
- `weave commit [<sha>|--since <ref>]` - record git commit(s) as milestones,
  with `produces` edges to any tracked files the commits touched.
- `weave projects` - other weave projects registered on this machine.
- `weave sync --scan --prune-missing` - import disk files + drop nodes
  whose paths no longer exist. `--scan` also auto-detects renames
  (same content hash -> repointed, edges preserved).

Keep the graph honest and current - it is what the human sees in
`weave serve`, and what you read next session.
<!-- weave:end -->
